[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 d5 (QGD, QGA, Slav, Semi-Slav, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queen's Gambit Declined"]
[Black "Exchange Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "01 1.d4 d5 (QGD, QGA, Slav, Semi-Slav, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33581"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 {The Queen's Gambit is a line every 1.d4 player should aspire to 
learn: White wastes no time in laying siege to Black's d-pawn! It's important to 
note that 2.c4 isn't a 'true' gambit because if 2...dxc4 Black can scarcely 
afford to hang on to the pawn (see the Queen's Gambit Accepted lines).} e6 {The 
Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) is one of Black's most respected defenses to 1. 
d4, and every World Champion in chess history has relied on it at some stage of 
their career. Black staunchly defends his center at the slight cost of locking 
in his light-square bishop.} 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 {The Exchange Variation. By 
capturing now, White ensures that he will be operating with an extra pawn in the 
center going forward (e+d vs. d).} exd5 5. Bg5 {Developing and pinning.} Be7 
({Breaking the pin. Black can also play} 5... Nbd7 {to which White should 
respond with} 6. e3 ({Not the well-known blunder} 6. Nxd5 $4 Nxd5 $1 7. Bxd8 
Bb4+ {winning back the queen with interest.})) 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 8. Qc2 
{Establishing a battery on the b1-h7 diagonal. White is now threatening to 
capture on f6, removing the defender of Black's h-pawn.} Nbd7 9. Nge2 {White has 
waited to commit this knight for good reason! 9.Nf3 is possible, but with 9.Nge2 
White has a specific plan in mind.} Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. f3 {The point of 
9.Nge2!. By placing a pawn on f3 White is planning to support the advance in the 
center, e3-e4. Preparatory moves like Ra1-d1 (e1) and h2-h3 (covering g4) can 
also be played prior to advancing. The plan of 'rolling' White with the e+f 
pawns was a favorite of former World Champion Garry Kasparov, who absolutely 
terrorized his opponents on the White side of the QGD. His games make for 
essential study!} *

