[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33582"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 {Top players often employ this savvy move order in 
order to circumvent the 'pure' Exchange Variation where White is allowed to play 
his bishop to g5.} 4. cxd5 {White still profits from this exchange.} exd5 5. Bf4 
{The next best square after g5. White plans harmonious development with e2-e3, 
Bf1-d3, Qd1-c2, and Ng1-e2 (f3).} c6 6. Qc2 $5 {A move order nuance designed to 
discourage ...Bc8-f5.} Nf6 7. h3 {Another subtlety! This time the idea is to 
prepare a safe retreat of the dark-square bishop to h2 in the case that Black 
harasses it with ...Nf6-h5.} O-O 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Bd3 Re8 10. Nf3 {10.Nge2 is also 
possible if White wants to adopt a plan of f2-f3 and e3-e4, as in the Exchange 
Variation.} Nf8 11. O-O {If you're an aggressive player you may gravitate toward 
10.0-0-0 and a kingside pawn storm!} Ng6 12. Bh2 Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Rab1 
{White is pursuing the 'Minority Attack' plan of b2-b4-b5, striving to create a 
weakness in Black's queenside formation.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 d5 (QGD, QGA, Slav, Semi-Slav, etc.)"]
