[White "Queen's Gambit Accepted"]
[Black "Greed Punished!"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "01 1.d4 d5 (QGD, QGA, Slav, Semi-Slav, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33583"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 {In my experience, the perfectly respectable Queen's Gambit 
Accepted (QGA) is far more popular at the lower levels than the higher echelons. 
The likely explanation is that novice players simply love to snatch material and 
ask questions later!} 3. e3 {Preparing to recapture with Bf1xc4. White has other 
alternatives, e.g. 3.e4, 3.Nf3, and 3.Nc3, although I'm recommending 3.e3 in 
this repertoire for simplicity's sake.} b5 $6 {Dubious, but White must know how 
to punish Black's determined defense of his ill-gotten gains.} 4. a4 $1 {A 
standard undermining move. When teaching a student, I often compare this 
operation to chopping down a tree. You wouldn't try to chop down a tree at the 
top; you must attack the base! With 4.a4 White tries to destabilize b5 and 
thereby bring about the 'toppling' of c4.} c6 {If Black wants to support the 
chain, then he must pin his hopes on the c-pawn, as 4... a6 5.axb5 axb5?? 6.Rxa8 
wins.} 5. axb5 cxb5 $4 6. Qf3 $1 {Oops! Black has been caught completely exposed 
on the h1-a8 diagonal and must surrender a piece. The possibility of this 
diagonal attack illustrates one nice point behind 3.e3 compared to 3.e4.} *

