[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33585"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 Nf6 {The most common choice on move three.} 4. Bxc4 e6 
5. Nf3 c5 {If Black does not strike at White's center, White will castle, 
develop, and arrange e3-e4.} 6. O-O a6 7. Bb3 {Prophylaxis against ...b7-b5. 
This is a theoretical branching point, so several other moves are possible} ({e. 
g. 7.a4, 7.Nc3, 7.dxc5, etc.}) {.} cxd4 ({7...Nc6 is similar, whereas} 7... b5 
$5 {could be met by the undermining reply} 8. a4) 8. exd4 {Fear not: as a 1.d4 
player you sometimes need to play isolated pawn positions in order to maximize 
your advantage!} Nc6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Bg5 {White has deployed the 
pieces effectively in an 'IQP' (Isolated Queen Pawn) structure. It's tough to 
generalize about the coming play, as many schemes are possible for White: a 
timely d4-d5 pawn break, propping a knight up on e5, creating a queen + bishop 
battery on the b1-h7 diagonal, and even h2-h4. A wonderful book for learning 
such plans is GM Alexander Baburin's 'Winning Pawn Structures'.} *

