1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 {The Tarrasch Defense. Black often ends up with an 
isolated d-pawn in this line, which has at times given the opening a poor and 
probably undeserved theoretical reputation.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3 
{Given the potentially weak d5-pawn (it is no longer defended by a fellow pawn), 
it makes sense for White to pursue a fianchettoed kingside bishop. On g2 it will 
be ideally placed to fire away at Black's center.} Nf6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. 
dxc5 {I'm recommending a simple system where White isolates Black's d-pawn and 
plays for control of c5.} Bxc5 10. Na4 Be7 11. Be3 {Focusing on c5.} Re8 12. Rc1 
{White has slightly better chances from this position. He can jump the knight 
(or possibly the dark-square bishop) in to c5 and may use d4 as a pivot point 
too (Nf3-d4).} *

