1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 {In the Slav Defense Black captures the 
pawn on c4 not with an outright intention to hold it, but rather to 
inconvenience White for a few moves in regaining the pawn. Black hopes to make 
use of this time to construct a solid setup.} 5. a4 {An unfortunate necessity, 
else Black will support the c-pawn with ...b7-b5. White should be aware that 
this pawn push weakens the b3 and b4 squares.} Bf5 6. e3 e6 7. Bxc4 Bb4 {If 
White's pawn still stood on a2, Black would not want to play this move.} 8. O-O 
O-O {8...Nbd7 could transpose.} 9. Qe2 {Preparing e3-e4. NOTE: White is not in a 
hurry to develop the dark-square bishop! In many 1.d4 lines it can be beneficial 
to let play develop before determining the destination for this bishop.} Nbd7 
10. e4 Bg6 11. Bd3 {Defusing Black's threat of capturing on c3 followed by e4. 
White could also play 11.e5, but there isn't a compelling reason to play this 
advance as of yet.} Bh5 12. e5 Nd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Qe3 {In practice White 
scores well from this theoretical position. He has a bit more space, and may 
continue on the queenside with Bc1-d2 and Rf1-c1, or on the kingside with 
Nf3-g5.} *

