1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {Black prepares ...b7-b5. While 
completely playable, this line doesn't seem to be too popular anymore.} 5. e3 b5 
6. b3 {I suggest a simple solution, reinforcing the c4-pawn.} Bg4 7. Qc2 
{Escaping the pin but accepting doubled pawns.} Bxf3 8. gxf3 Nbd7 9. f4 
{Clamping the e5-square so Black cannot break with 9...e5.} e6 10. c5 {Clamping 
down once again! It seems counterintuitive to close the position when in 
possession of the bishop pair, but White can look forward to squeezing Black. 
I've played this way quite often in blitz with good results.} g6 11. Bd3 Bg7 12. 
Bb2 O-O 13. O-O-O {Black's structure is durable, but White is having a bit more 
fun here. One popular idea is to re-route the knight to the center: Nc3-e2-g1-f3 
and eventually Nf3-e5. White may break in the center with e3-e4 at some stage as 
well.} *

