1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 g6 {World Champion Vasily Smyslov often 
played this Slav/Grunfeld hybrid. I've never thought this line to be too 
troubling to White, however.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 $1 {Transferring the game to a 
favorable version of the Exchange Slav.} 6. Bf4 {Preparing to follow with e2-e3, 
when the bishop is nicely situated outside the pawn chain.} Bg7 7. e3 {White 
could also think about the immediate 7.h3!?, giving the bishop the h2 retreat 
square. However, after 7.e3 White need not be overly concerned about 7...Nh5 
(chasing the bishop) since 8.Be5} ({or perhaps even 8.Bxb8!? Rxb8 9.Qa4+, 
winning the a-pawn}) {is a reliable reply.} O-O 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. h3 {Preparing a 
cubby hole for the bishop on h2 while simultaneously preventing ...Bc8-g4. White 
stands better thanks to his superior bishops.} *

