[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33590"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 {In The Semi-Slav Defense Black 
reinforces d5 even further but does not yet declare his intentions. There's a 
decent chance Black will still snatch the c-pawn if allowed, and therefore many 
White players prefer 5.e3 at this juncture.} 5. cxd5 {After some deliberation, 
I've decided to recommend this simple capture. In this way White can play 
without worrying about a capture on c4} ({compare this to the hyper-sharp 
Botvinnik Variation, 5.Bg5 dxc4}) {.} exd5 6. Qc2 $5 {Ruling out ... Bc8-f5 for 
the time being.} g6 {Black is persistent!} 7. Bg5 Be7 {Instead, 7... Bf5?! would 
have been a mistake in view of 8.Qb3, hitting b7. Black would love to respond 
with 8...Qb6, but f6 would hang.} 8. e4 $5 {Uncompromising! If White were to 
'settle' with 8.e3, then 8...Bf5 comes. In the Carlsbad pawn structure Black 
generally has no issues if he manages to get his bishop to f5 and/or exchange 
for White's light-square bishop.} dxe4 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qxe4+ Qe7 {It's also 
possible for Black to run the king to g7 with 10...Kf8. Here too White may play 
Bf1-c4 and 0-0-0.} 11. Bc4 Bf5 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. O-O-O {Many games end in draws 
from here, though I'd rather be White due to his potential for a slight 
initiative. The king's rook could make a quick appearance on e1, and h2-h3 
(intending g2-g4) and Nf3-e5 are possible plans.} *

