[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33605"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 {In the Chigorin Variation Black breaks a loose 'rule' of 1. 
d4 openings in putting his knight on c6 with a pawn on c7. He instead angles to 
quickly attack White's center with his knight and possibly his queen} ({in the 
event of 3.cxd5 Qxd5}) {.} 3. Nf3 {A stable response. White defends d4 and also 
controls the e5 square.} Bg4 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bf4 Bxf3 {If Black does not play this 
capture now, then White will play 6.e3 and defend f3 with the queen as well.} 6. 
gxf3 Bd6 7. Bg3 {A useful retreat to remember. Should Black play 7...Bxg3, White 
can slightly improve his structure with 8.hxg3.} Nge7 8. e3 {White scores well 
here. In addition to simple play like c4xd5/Bf1-d3/0-0, White may also consider 
c4-c5.} *

