[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33607"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 {The Triangle Variation can be thought of as a 
tricky QGD/Semi-Slav hybrid where Black tries to benefit from keeping his knight 
on g8. If White continues with 4.Nf3, Black can steer the game toward the highly 
complex Noteboom Variation with 4...dxc4.} 4. cxd5 {Just as in the Semi-Slav, 
this exchange simplifies White's task.} exd5 5. Qc2 {A transposition to a 
Queen's Gambit Declined-like position is possible, e.g.} Nf6 6. Bg5 Be7 7. e3 *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 d5 (QGD, QGA, Slav, Semi-Slav, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Triangle Variation II"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "01 1.d4 d5 (QGD, QGA, Slav, Semi-Slav, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33608"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 e6 {The only distinguishing feature of this position 
and the position on move 3 in the previous line is the knight White has 
developed. Here Black has entered the Triangle with a Slav move order, so White 
has already committed the knight to f3.} 4. Qc2 {A decent way to defend c4 that 
doesn't clash with our repertoire. Instead, 4.Nc3 would invite the Noteboom 
Variation with 4...dxc4, and 4.e3 would require White to have knowledge of the 
Meran or Anti-Meran Variations of the Semi-Slav.} Nf6 {4...dxc4 is also 
possible, but I suspect you're more likely to encounter opponents who simply 
develop.} 5. g3 {With c4 reliably protected, White has the freedom to fianchetto 
the bishop and eventually play for e2-e4. By contrast, 5.e3 would block the 
dark-square bishop and cut down on White's play.} Nbd7 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. 
Nbd2 {White is geared up for e2-e4. He can either play this next move, or 
include his dark-square bishop in the struggle with b2-b3 and Bc1-b2.} *

