1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5 {Quoting Wikipedia (please forgive me! :)), .'It the 
Symmetrical Defense poses the purest test of Queen's Gambit theory—whether 
Black can equalize by simply copying White's moves.' Personally, I've often 
found trying to equalize a tempo down in symmetric positions (or near symmetric 
positions) to be a risky proposition.} 3. cxd5 Qxd5 {Not 3...cxd4? 4. Qxd4, 
protecting d5.} 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nc3 {Making use of the pinned d-pawn.} Qa5 6. 
Nxd4 Nf6 7. Bd2 {Don't feel the need to study any further. Basic chess 
principles dictate to us that White must be better! 7.Nb3 followed by 8.e4 is an 
alternate way to play, by the way.} e5 *

