1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bf5 $6 {This faulty bishop development is 
often seen at the amateur level. Black's intentions are pure - develop the 
bishop outside the pawn chain prior to ...e7-e6 - but his timing is poor. White 
can now gain an advantage.} 5. cxd5 $1 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Hitting Black where it 
hurts: b7 and d5.} Qb6 {Objectively best for Black is the abject retreat 
6...Bc8, but I haven't encountered too many players willing to embarass 
themselves like this! :) Needless to say, White will be better with simple play} 
({I'd start with 7.Bf4}) {. Note that 6...Qd7 is punished by 7.Ne5, when Black 
cannot successfully defend both pawns.} 7. Nxd5 Nxd5 {On 7...Qxb3 White has the 
important in-between move 8.Nxf6+.} 8. Qxd5 e6 9. Qb3 Qxb3 10. axb3 Bc2 11. Bd2 
Bxb3 12. e4 {Black has regained the pawn, but his position is in jeopardy. Next 
White will play Bb5(+), castle short, and play Rf1-c1. Black is struggling to 
coordinate.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 d5 (QGD, QGA, Slav, Semi-Slav, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
