[White "The Faulty 4...Bf5 Slav II"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "01 1.d4 d5 (QGD, QGA, Slav, Semi-Slav, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/234642"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bf5 $6 {This faulty bishop development is 
often seen at the amateur level. Black's intentions are pure - develop the 
bishop outside the pawn chain prior to ...e7-e6 - but his timing is poor. White 
can now gain an advantage.} 5. cxd5 $1 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Hitting Black where it 
hurts: b7 and d5.} b6 {Defending b7, but amazingly this move is practically 
losing!} 7. e4 {Yes! The move 6...b6 weakens the a4-e8 diagonal leading to 
Black's king, so White hastens to open lines. In the following tactical 
blitzkrieg you just need to know a few details.} dxe4 {Every capture leads to 
disaster: 7...Nxe4 8.Nxe4 dxe4 9.Ne5 Be6 10.Bb5+ Nd7 11.d5 Bf5 12.g4 +- Black's 
bishop is vital to the defense of d7, and it just ran out of safe squares; 
7...Bxe4 8.Bb5+ Nfd7 9.Nxe4 dxe4 10.Ng5 e6 11.d5! with threats of 12.dxe6 and 
12.Nxf7 White is dominating.} 8. Ne5 {Threatening 9.Qxf7#!} e6 {8...Be6 9.Bb5+ 
Nfd7 10.d5 Bf5 11.g4 is similar to 7...Nxe4.} 9. Bb5+ Nbd7 10. Bg5 {After 
seemingly natural moves, Black is busted. There is no reasonable defense to the 
capture on f6 followed by a capture on d7. 10.g4 is also very strong, by the 
way.} Be7 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Nxd7 {White is winning.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 d5 (QGD, QGA, Slav, Semi-Slav, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
