[White "Accelerated Ragozin"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "01 1.d4 d5 (QGD, QGA, Slav, Semi-Slav, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/425875"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {Historically, this early bishop development has 
been thought to be dubious. Compared to a Nimzo-Indian, White has less to fear 
strategically because the tension between the c4 and d5 pawns means that a 
bishop for knight trade on c3 won't saddle White with permanently doubled 
c-pawns. Despite this, Bb4 is occasionally played by strong players and has been 
re-examined in recent years in books like 'Playing the Ragozin' by Richard 
Pert.} 4. a3 {The straightforward approach. White welcomes a trade on c3 because 
the doubled pawns are only temporary and the bishop pair is a long-lasting 
asset. 4. Qa4+ is another good option, forcing Nc6, which blocks Black's c-pawn. 
4. Nf3 could lead to the proper Ragozin Defense after 4.. .Nf6.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 
Nf6 {Black sometimes tries 5...Ne7 or 5...c5, but White can develop similarly 
against these moves. Against 5...dxc4 White can regain the pawn immediately with 
6. Qa4+ or play 6. e3/6. e4. Just like in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, it's 
dangerous for Black to get greedy and play to hold the c4-pawn.} 6. e3 {White 
plans to proceed as follows: c4xd5, Bf1-d3, Ng1-e2, and O-O.} O-O 7. cxd5 {This 
capture is timely, since Black may try to drag the bishop to c4 with ...d5xc4 if 
White starts with 7. Bd3.} exd5 8. Bd3 c5 {Attempting to apply pressure on 
White's center. b6 is similar.} 9. Ne2 b6 10. O-O Ba6 11. f3 {White will now 
focus on preparing the e3-e4 pawn break with Ne2-g3 and perhaps even the 
exotic-looking Ra1-a2-e2! White's dark-square bishop is the only 'problem' 
piece, but it could be activated after e3-e4 or even prove useful on the a1-h8 
diagonal (Bc1-b2) after the smoke clears in the center (this bishop development 
may facilitate an additional way the queenside rook can get involved, Ra1-e1) . 
See the game Navara - Sturua, European Championship 2016 for an instructive 
demonstration of White's play in this middlegame.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nimzo - Classical Main Line"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33591"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {I consider the Nimzo-Indian to be the best 
all-around defense to 1.d4. The concept of influencing the center with pieces 
rather pawns was first espoused by Aron Nimzowitsch in 1920s, and nearly one 
hundred years of tournament practice has validated his ideas.} 4. Qc2 {The 
Classical (Capablanca) Variation is an easy recommendation. White spends a tempo 
on an early queen move, but he avoids the pawn structure damage (...Bxc3 bxc3) 
that is the wheelhouse of virtually every Nimzo-Indian player. Black now has a 
few different moves, so I'll examine them in separate variations.} O-O {Castling 
is the most flexible and common.} 5. a3 {The natural follow-up to 4.Qc2. A good 
alternative is 5.Nf3.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 {Black has other possibilities} 
({6...d6, 6...d5, 6...Ne4, even 6...b5!?}) {, but the text is by far the most 
popular. Black will establish his light-square bishop on the h1-a8 diagonal, 
play ...d7-d6, ...Nb8-d7, and (probably) a later ...c7-c5.} 7. Bg5 {Pinning the 
Black knight and readying e2-e3.} Bb7 8. e3 d6 9. Ne2 {Refined. Developing the 
knight to f3 is far more natural, but the knight has few prospects on that 
square. Instead, the steed is bound for c3, where it will better influence 
matters on the queenside while supporting pawn incursions like d4-d5 and e3-e4.} 
Nbd7 10. Qc2 {Making room for the knight.} c5 11. Rd1 {Opposing Black's queen. 
Here we have a typical theoretical battleground in the Nimzo-Indian: White has 
two bishops yet lags slightly in development, whereas Black has a solid position 
but cannot control the proceedings as well as White. The first player will 
likely continue with 12.Nc3, when further play very much depends on whether 
Black tries to change the pawn structure in the center before White can complete 
development (Bf1-e2, 0-0) or play d4-d5.} *

