1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 {Like the Nimzo-Indian, the Grunfeld Defense is 
another 1.d4 opening with the highest possible theoretical reputation. My usual 
strategy with White against this opening is to vary my play every once in 
awhile, as I don't consider any single line to be the true test of the Grunfeld. 
Here I'm recommending a straightforward line leading to a 'tabiya' (essentially 
a major theoretical position/branching point), after which play can proceed in 
many different directions depending upon what Black does. If you're a bit 
higher-rated, you may therefore want to do some of your own research beyond move 
10!} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 {Black is allowing White to occupy the center, but 
he plans on attacking it from a distance with ...Bf8-g7, ...c7-c5, and 
...Nb8-c6.} 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 {I like this destination for the knight 
because it avoids a potential pin with ...Bc8-g4.} Nc6 9. Be3 {Supporting the 
critical d4 pawn.} O-O 10. O-O {We have reached our tabiya. If allowed, White 
can continue with improving moves like Qd1-d2, Ra1-c1, Rf1-d1, etc., but as I 
said earlier there are many ways Black can play at this stage. For beginners you 
are on solid theoretical ground and can now just 'play chess', but I'd encourage 
higher-rated players to do their own investigation from here.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33596"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 {The provocative King's Indian sees Black refusing 
to even bat an eye about White's central expansion! Fighters like Bobby Fischer, 
Svetozar Gligoric, and Garry Kasparov molded the King's Indian in to a 
formidable weapon during their careers, whereas more classically-minded players 
often suggested that the opening was unsound (Tigran Petrosian famously quipped 
that he was able to feed his family in playing White against the King's 
Indian).} 4. e4 {Of course White should take the space on offer.} d6 5. Nf3 O-O 
6. Be2 {One question I've received before is 'why e2 and not d3'? Well, on e2 
the bishop hedges against a potential ... Bc8-g4 pin, and the bishop does not 
interfere with the White queen's defense of d4.} e5 {The Classical Variation. 
Here 7.0-0 leads to mountains of complex theory, so I'm recommending a (surprise 
surprise!) simplifying line that tends to frustrate King's Indian players (who 
usually want a gritty fight!).} 7. dxe5 dxe5 {Trade!} 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Nd5 
{Without this move White would have no chance for an advantage. Now Black is 
advised to capture on d5, as White is hitting c7 and 10.Bg5 is also a threat.} 
Nxd5 10. cxd5 {The d5 pawn has a cramping effect, so Black ought to undermine 
it.} c6 11. Bc4 {Supporting d5.} cxd5 {Another popular line is 11...b5 12.Bb3 
Bb7 13.Bg5, gaining a tempo on the rook. A model game with that continuation is 
Nakamura - Adhiban, World Cup 2013.} 12. Bxd5 {White may next play Bc1-Bg5 and 
0-0-0. He may castle on either wing, or even keep the king in the center in 
preparation for the endgame. Over-the-board statistics and the engines all 
indicate that the position is close to level. Why bother playing this line, 
then? Well, the practical advantage is that you - the White player - will be 
familiar with the Exchange Variation and look forward to playing this queenless 
middlegame, whereas Black often dreads this simplified line and may not be too 
familiar with its subtleties.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
