[White "Benko Gambit 5...axb5"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33602"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 {In the Benko Gambit Black offers a pawn for 
queenside play. The main line sees White accepting the pawn with 4.cxb5 a6 5. 
bxa6, but there are some nice 'middle of the road' options where White captures 
the first pawn but not the second.} 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 {Defending b5. As a 
sometimes-Benko Gambit player, I can attest that Black does not have an easy 
life against this line.} axb5 {This initiates a forcing sequence.} 6. Bxb5 Qa5+ 
7. Nc3 Bb7 8. Bd2 Qb6 {Note that 8...Nxd5?? 9.Nxd5 Qxb5 loses to 10.Nc7+.} 9. 
Nf3 {Development above all else! White returns the pawn, but capturing it 
requires Black to neglect his development.} Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. a4 e6 12. Bc3 
{The bishop is well-placed on this diagonal.} Be7 {Recognizing that White cannot 
favorably capture on g7 due to 13...Rg8 and 14...Rxg2.} 13. O-O O-O 14. Nd2 {I 
like White's position. e3-e4 and Nd2-c4 is a nice plan, and if Black plays to 
prevent this with 14...f5, then 15.f3 will soon renew the threatened e-pawn 
advance.} *

