1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 g6 {A real Benko Gambit response. 
Black is not concerned about getting his pawn back. White should keep an 
advantage this way, however.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. a4 {In almost every case 
a2-a4 is a nice move to have. In addition to overprotecting b5, Ra1-a3 may be a 
useful lift.} Bb7 9. e4 {This is a theoretical parting of the ways. I'm 
recommending 9.e4 because it's direct, but 9.Ra3 and 9.Be2 are also played.} e6 
{Black is down a pawn with less space, so he can't afford to sit around and give 
White time to develop and consolidate.} 10. Bc4 {The engine prefers White here, 
and White's 6-1 score from this position is promising.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
