[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33604"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 {There are many 
reasonable systems at White's disposal against the Benoni Defense. The following 
line is one I first learned from IM John Cox's excellent work 'Starting Out: 
1.d4'.} g6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. h3 {Restricting Black's light-square bishop. In this 
opening Black is typically happy if they can exchange a pair of minor pieces, as 
this eases the congestion he currently experiences (for instance, if Black were 
to play ...Nbd7 he would block the light-square bishop) . Thus, playing to 
prevent ...Bc8-g4xf3} ({as would happen in the case of 8.Nf3 Bg4}) {makes life 
difficult for Black.} O-O 9. Nf3 {From here White looks to castle and play 
Bc1-f4. An eventual e4-e5 pawn break (likely supported by Rf1-e1) is especially 
desirable. One good rule of thumb is that if Black ever plays ...a7-a6, White 
should respond with a2-a4 in order to prevent expansion with ...b7-b5. For 
advanced players I will note that Black can play 9...b5!? at this juncture, 
which invites forcing play after 10.Nxb5 or 10.Bxb5 (both captures are 
playable).} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
