[White "Czech Benoni Defense"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33611"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 {The Czech Benoni differs markedly when compared to 
the conventional Benoni. Here Black will establish a chain of pawns on 
dark-squares and seek to keep the position closed for the time being.} 4. Nc3 d6 
5. e4 Be7 6. g3 {Putting the bishop on, say, d3 doesn't inspire because of the 
pawns on e4 and c4. True, the bishop isn't greatly improved on g2 (it's White's 
bad bishop, after all), but playing 6.g3 does assist with a future f2-f4 break.} 
O-O 7. Bg2 Ne8 {A common maneuver. Black readies a King's-Indian like ...f7-f5 
pawn break, although first he may play ...g7-g6 and put the knight on g7 (also 
seen in the Chigorin Variation of the Ruy Lopez).} 8. Nge2 Nd7 9. O-O g6 10. Bh6 
Ng7 11. Qd2 {Now if Black plays 11...f5 White can respond with 12.f4! and the 
first player will be better coordinated when the center explodes. Should Black 
refrain from ...f7-f5 White can go ahead with f2-f4 anyways.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Budapest Gambit - Main Line"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/79621"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5 {The Budapest Gambit. Black offers a pawn to destroy White's 
c4+d4 duo. This gift should be accepted, of course!} 3. dxe5 Ng4 4. Bf4 {I 
believe this is a stronger and more harmonious continuation than the popular 
4.Nf3. White simultaneously develops and defends e5, and when e2-e3 is played 
this bishop will not feel shut in.} Nc6 {Sometimes Black ventures 4...g5!? 5.Bg3 
Bg7. I would then recommend 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.h4!?, trying to profit from Black's 
shaky g-pawn.} 5. Nf3 Bb4+ 6. Nc3 $5 {An important decision. It appears more 
logical to play 6.Nbd2, but this would block the White queen's access to d5. We 
are planning on making it as difficult as possible for Black to regain the 
e5-pawn!} Bxc3+ {6...Qe7 can transpose, e.g. 7.Qd5 f6 8.exf6 Nxf6 9.Qd3 Bxc3+ 
10.bxc3 etc.} 7. bxc3 Qe7 8. Qd5 $1 {Centralization with purpose! White defends 
e5, and if Black leisurely castles, then h2-h3 will leave the second player 
looking silly.} f6 {With no realistic way to continue the assault on e5 Black 
agrees to play a pawn down.} 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. Qd3 d6 11. g3 {Fianchettoing the 
light-square bishop is appropriate since the bishop will not be inhibited by 
many pawns on the h1-a8 diagonal.} O-O 12. Bg2 {With the two bishops and an 
extra pawn, White enjoys the better game. Black can claim some compensation in 
the form of White's weakened structure, but in practice White scores 60-80% from 
this position.} *

