1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 Ne4 {The Fajarowicz Variation. This line is trappier 
than 3...Ng4, so beware!} 4. Nf3 Bb4+ {On 4...Nc6, I recommend 5.Nbd2} ({5.a3!? 
is possibly stronger, but it is much sharper}) {when 5...Bb4 6.a3 would 
transpose. Alternatively, 4...Bc5 would be met by 5.e3.} 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. a3 
{Forcing simplifications.} Bxd2+ 7. Bxd2 Nxd2 8. Qxd2 Qe7 9. Qc3 {As in the main 
line, we're not giving up e5 without a fight! In view of the coming maneuver, c3 
is a good post for White's queen.} O-O 10. Rd1 Re8 11. Rd5 {Just in time! Black 
experiences difficulties regaining the pawn, and White plans to complete 
development with e2-e3, Bf1-e2, and 0-0.} *

