[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/88056"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {Several 
Chessable users wrote to me asking how to counter this early knight jump. Black 
intends to rapidly expand and support his knight with ...f7-f5, so we must have 
a plan to evict this pesky steed!} 7. Qc2 f5 8. Nh3 $5 {I like this idea. Since 
the immediate 8.f3? fails to 8...Qh4+ 9.g3 Nxg3, White develops and prepares the 
f-pawn push. The knight is only temporarily bad on h3, and it often gets 
re-positioned to f2.} d6 9. f3 Nf6 {Note that 9...Qh4+? just loses material 
after 10.g3 Nxg3 11.hxg3 (no hanging rook on h1!).} 10. e3 {Supporting the 
center and readying the development of the light-square bishop.} e5 11. dxe5 
dxe5 12. Be2 {White has a modest edge. Next he will castle and think about 
b2-b4(b3), Bc1-b2, Ra1-d1, Nh3-f2, etc. Black has more central space at present, 
but don't be fooled: White's bishops are valuable middlegame tools!} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nimzo-Indian Defense, 5...Na6"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 1.d4 Nf6 (Nimzo-Indian, Gruenfeld, KID, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/425876"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 {Striking the undefended d-pawn.} 5. 
dxc5 {In the 4. Qc2 Nimzo White's best bet is usually to play dxc5 when 
prompted.} Na6 {Planning to recapture on c5 with the knight.} 6. a3 Bxc3+ {Less 
critical alternatives are Qa5 and Bxc5.} 7. Qxc3 Nxc5 {Like most lines in the 4. 
Qc2 Nimzo-Indian, Black now enjoys an appreciable lead in development. White 
ought to have better chances, but the following line is important to know. Black 
will have a temporary initiative, but fear not!} 8. b4 {Against routine 
development Black may sneak in ...a7-a5-a4, cementing his knight and paralyzing 
White's queenside majority.} Nce4 9. Qb2 {Maintaining control of the a1-h8 
diagonal.} d5 {Against 9... O-O White can favorably advance in the center: 10. 
f3 Nd6 11. e4.} 10. c5 $1 {Now 11. f3 is a significant threat.} d4 {Attempting 
to create an outpost on c3.} 11. e3 {Undermining the d4-pawn and opening the 
light-square bishop.} e5 12. Nf3 {12. Bb5+ is also a decent option.} O-O 13. 
Nxe5 $1 {This position has been reached a few times in over-the-board play, with 
White scoring 4.5/6. Though still ahead in development, I don't see how Black 
claims compensation for the pawn and bishop pair. If allowed, White will next 
play Bf1-c4 (d3) and O-O. If Black captures on e3, then Bc1xe3 further spurs 
White's development. Stockfish is also unconvinced of Black's compensation and 
gives White a comfortable +1.3 advantage.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Dutch Defense 2...Nf6"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33597"]

1. d4 f5 {The Dutch Defense has traditionally had a slightly dodgy reputation. 
This makes sense, since Black has already moved the 'forget about it' pawn! 
However, in my opinion this opening is entirely legitimate.} 2. Nc3 {Against the 
Dutch Defense theory considers a kingside fianchetto to be one of White's best 
paths, and lines like the Leningrad Variation have amassed quite a bit of 
theory. However, White has other perfectly valid approaches, which is why I'm 
recommending an easy-to-play system with 2.Nc3.} Nf6 3. Bg5 {A mirror image of 
the Rossolimo Sicilian! White plans to swap his dark-square bishop for Black's 
knight and thereby weaken Black's structure.} d5 4. Bxf6 exf6 5. e3 {The 
following development scheme is thematic for this line.} Be6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Qf3 
{Attacking f5.} Qd7 8. a3 O-O-O 9. Nge2 g6 10. Nf4 {White has achieved a typical 
configuration. He has pressure on Black's pawns and will most likely castle 
long, play h2-h4 and, perhaps a later h4-h5. White should take care not to open 
the position unnecessarily, as Black's bishop pair may come to life.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
