[Round "?"]
[White "Dutch Defense 3...e6"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33598"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 e6 {Now Black's queen is defending f6, so it doesn't 
make as much sense for White to capture.} 4. e4 {This position can also be 
reached via 2.e4 (the Staunton Gambit).} fxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. Nf3 
O-O 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. c3 {Due to his control of the center, White has a slightly 
more pleasant position. An ambitious plan is to play Qd1-c2 (or possibly 
Qd1-e2), castle queenside, and attack Black on the kingside!} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Dutch Defense 2...d5"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33599"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 {Here 3.Bg5 would send the bishop 'in to thin air', so 
f4 is a smarter choice.} Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Nb5 $5 {Normally you should avoid early 
knight moves in to your opponent's half of the board because they are often 
easily rebuffed. However, here White aims to gain a tempo by attacking c7 in 
order to gain time for c2-c4. Even if the knight retreats back to c3, this 
structure (pawn on c4, knight on c3) is desirable due to the pressure White 
generates on d5.} Na6 6. c4 c6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 {White can try to 
make use of the e5 square, and Black has a poor light-square bishop. A queenside 
expansion play (a2-a3, b2-b4) could also be on the first player's radar. White 
stands better.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Dutch Defense"]
[Black "Stonewall Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33600"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 {A tricky move order to enter the Dutch Defense. Black is 
sidestepping many of the lines that can be problematic after 1.d4 f5.} 3. g3 Nf6 
4. Bg2 c6 {Black also often plays the immediate 4...d5, which would tranpose.} 
5. Nf3 d5 6. O-O Bd6 7. b3 {In the Stonewall Variation Black establishes his 
pawns on light squares and set his sights on the e4 outpost. White is best 
advised to counter on the dark squares, and this move seeks a favorable trade of 
dark-square bishops with Bc1-a3.} Qe7 {For the moment, Black prevents White's 
plan.} 8. a4 {Adding another defender to a3 and renewing Bc1-a3.} a5 9. Ba3 Bxa3 
10. Nxa3 {White has successfully swapped the bishops and can therefore be 
optimistic about utilizing the e5 square. Peering further in to the future, pawn 
breaks like b3-b4 and e2-e3/f2-f3/e3-e4 could be pursued.} *

