[White "Dutch Defense"]
[Black "Classical Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33601"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O d6 {Despite his 
modest-looking setup, Black often has dangerous attacking aspirations in the 
Classical Variation. English GM Simon Williams (the 'Ginger GM'!) has defeated 
titans like Boris Gelfand with this line!} 7. b3 {A double fianchetto approach 
is appropriate against this line, as it will frustrate Black's attempt to play 
...e6-e5.} Qe8 {This is Black's principal attacking continuation; he plans ... 
Qe8-h5.} 8. Bb2 Qh5 9. Nbd2 {White also plays 9.Nc3, but I believe the 
development to d2 is harmonious.} Nc6 10. e3 Bd7 11. Ne1 {A nice repositioning 
(the knight is headed to d3) that also proposes a queen trade.} Qxd1 12. Rxd1 
{White's knight will land on d3, after which White can expand on the queenside 
with his pawns. White's position is undoubtedly for choice.} *

