[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33610"]

1. d4 g6 2. e4 {Many 1.d4 players prefer the consistent 2.c4, but I believe it's 
simpler (and possibly objectively better) to take the center with 2.e4.} Bg7 3. 
Nc3 d6 {An alternative is 3...c6, the Gurgenidze Variation.} 4. Nf3 {Simple 
development.} Nf6 5. Be2 {5.Bc4 looks more attractive, but that invites the 
'center fork trick' with 5...0-0 6.0-0 Nxe4 7.Nxe4 d5.} O-O 6. O-O {This 
position has been reached thousands of times in practice. White has slightly the 
better chances with his central control.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Keres Defense"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33612"]

1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {Rarely played. Transpositions to a Bogo-Indian abound.} 3. 
Bd2 a5 {Most popular. 3...Qe7 and 3...Bxd2+ are also tried.} 4. a3 {White can 
play either 4.Nc3 or 4.Nf3, but the text is fine and - bonus - easy to 
remember!} Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 {When confronted with an early bishop capture on d2, it 
often makes sense for White to re-capture with the queen so the knight can 
develop to the more active c3 square. You see the same philosophy in the Moscow 
Variation of the Sicilian Defense: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.Bb5+ Bd7 4.Bxd7+ and here 
4...Qxd7 is regarded as best by theory.} Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Nf3 {Setups in the 
Nimzo/Bogo/Queen's Indian family are notoriously tough to crack, although the 
central space Black cedes usually translates to a small plus for White. This 
position is no exception. White can think about seizing even more territory with 
e2-e4 next, or he could fianchetto his light-square bishop and keep the e-pawn 
back.} *

