1. d4 d6 {Sometimes King's Indian Defense players use this move order, although 
here we'll see an entirely independent treatment.} 2. Nf3 Bg4 {Wait, what 
happened to the old maxim of 'knights before bishops'!? :)} 3. e4 {Other tries} 
({like 3.c3 and 3.g3}) {are also possible, but I like the text. Throughout this 
repertoire I've recommended grabbing central space whenever possible, as an 
improving player will achieve his/her best results with this classical 
approach.} Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Be2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. h3 Bh5 8. Re1 {White has a 
pleasant game.} *

