[White "Englund Gambit"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33614"]

1. d4 e5 $2 {The Englund Gambit contains a trap on move six, but objectively 
it's close to losing. Just be sure to memorize this line!} 2. dxe5 Nc6 3. Nf3 
Qe7 4. Bf4 {4.Bg5 is also good. Both bishop moves underscore the fact that White 
should not be afraid of 4...Qb4+.} Qb4+ {Black will win the b-pawn and establish 
material equality, but this costs him a lot of time.} 5. Bd2 Qxb2 6. Nc3 $1 
{Development is the name of the game, and White's knight has its sights set on 
c7. Avoid the well-known clunker 6.Bc3?? Bb4 7.Qd2 Bxc3 8.Qxc3 Qc1 mate!} Bb4 7. 
Rb1 Qa3 8. Nd5 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Qxa2 10. Rd1 Kd8 11. e4 {Black is now up a pawn, 
but his position is hardly tenable. White will complete development with Bf1-e2 
and 0-0, after which Black's atrocious coordination will be the second player's 
downfall. Indeed, Stockfish already rates White's advantage as greater than +2.} 
*

