2.d5 or 2.e4, but White has a simple alternative.} 2. Nf3 {Controlling e5. Now 
Black's best bet is probably to transpose to the Chigorin Variation with 
2...d5.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's 1.d4 Repertoire for White"]
[Site "Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Polish Defense"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Less Common Defenses (Dutch, Modern, etc.)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-1d4-repertoire-for-white/course/102, variation/33618"]

1. d4 b5 {Pushing the limits of Black's respectable replies to 1.d4! Actually, 
this defense isn't as bad as it looks. White can demonstrate a clean advantage, 
however.} 2. e4 Bb7 {Sometimes Black plays 2...a6.} 3. Bxb5 {If White doesn't 
want to play ball, then 3.Nd2 is perfectly good as well. Note that if White 
plans to develop the queenside knight, then c3 should be avoided on account of 
...b5-b4.} Bxe4 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 {Before developing the knight, White 
guarantees more central influence.} Be7 7. Nc3 Bb7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Ba4 
{Prophylaxis. White would like to play d4-d5 to shut out Black's light-square 
bishop, but on 9.d5 the reply 9...c6! gives Black sufficient play.} d6 10. d5 
{Snuffing out Black's b7 bishop. If 10...e5, then 11.c5! is excellent, 
accelerating White's play with the pawn majority on the queenside.} *

